{{Infobox ancient site |name = Arkaim |native_name = Аркаим {{ru icon}} |alternate_name = |image = Аркаим_2015.jpg |alt = |caption = Aerial view of the main citadel |map_type = European Russia#Russia |map_alt = Arkaim site in Russia |map_size =240 |relief = yes |coordinates = {{coord|52|38|57.34|N|59|34|17.194|E|display=inline,title}} |location = [[Bredinsky District]], [[Chelyabinsk Oblast]], [[Russia]] |region = [[Kazakh Steppe]] |type = Settlement |part_of = |length = |width = |area = {{convert|2|ha|abbr=on}} |height = |builder = |material = |built = |abandoned = |epochs = [[Bronze Age]] |cultures = [[Sintashta culture]] |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = |archaeologists = [[Gennady Zdanovich]] |condition = |ownership = Public |management = |public_access = Yes |website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> |notes = }} {{Indo-European}} '''Arkaim''' ({{lang-ru|Аркаим}}) is an [[archaeological site]] in Russia, situated in the steppe of the [[Southern Ural]], {{convert|8.2|km|mi|2|abbr=on}} north-to-northwest of the village of Amursky and {{convert|2.3|km|mi|2|abbr=on}} south-to-southeast of the village of Alexandrovsky in the [[Chelyabinsk Oblast]] of [[Russia]], just north of the border with [[Kazakhstan]]. It was discovered in 1987 by a team of archaeologists led by [[Gennady Zdanovich]], preventing the planned flooding of the area for the creation of a reservoir.{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=33}} Arkaim is attributed to the early [[Proto-Indo-European|Indo-Europeans]] of the [[Sintashta culture]], which some scholars believe represents the proto-[[Indo-Iranians]] before their split into different groups and migration to Central Asia and from there to [[Persia]] and [[India]] and other parts of Eurasia (see [[Indo-Aryan migration theory]]).{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=35}}
Scholars have identified the structure of Arkaim as the cities built "reproducing the model of the universe" described in ancient Indo-European spiritual literature, the [[Vedas]] and the [[Avesta]].{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=35}} The structure consists of three concentric rings of walls and three radial streets, reflecting the city of [[King Yima]] described in the [[Rigveda]].{{sfn|Jones-Bley|Zdanovich|2002|p=45}} The foundation walls and the dwellings of the second ring are built according to ''[[swastika]]''-like patterns;{{sfn|Jones-Bley|Zdanovich|2002|p=163}} the same symbol is found on various artefacts.{{sfn|Jones-Bley|Zdanovich|2002|p=324}} Arkaim is designated as a "national and spiritual shrine" of Russia{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=35}} and has become a holy site for [[Rodnover]], [[Zoroastrian]] and other religious movements.{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=38}}
The fortified citadel of Arkaim dates back to the 17th and 16th century BCE. More than twenty other structures built according to similar patterns have been found in a larger area spanning from the southern Urals' region to the north of Kazakhstan, forming the so-called "[[Country of Towns|Land of Towns]]".{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=34}} Artefacts found at these sites date between the 4th millennium and the 20th century BCE.<ref name=MSU>{{cite web |title=Arkaim the Forgotten Valley |year=2002 |url=http://anthropology.msu.edu/anp264-ss13/2013/04/24/arkaim-the-forgotten-valley/ |publisher=Michigan State University, Department of Anthropology |website=anthropology.msu.edu}}</ref> In 2005, the city of Arkaim was visited by [[Vladimir Putin]].{{sfn|Shnirelman|2012|pp=27–28}}
==Discovery and salvage of the site== In the summer of the year 1987 a team of archaeologists headed by [[Gennady Zdanovich]] was sent to examine the archaeological value of the valley at the confluence of the Bolshaya Karaganka and Utyaganka rivers, in the south of [[Chelyabinsk Oblast]] or the [[Southern Ural]] region, where the construction of a reservoir had begun the previous autumn. Some archaeological sites in the area were already known, but they had yielded little and were not considered worthy of preservation. The site would have been flooded by the spring of 1988.{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=33}}
On June 20, two students who took part in the expedition, Aleksandr Voronkov and Aleksandr Ezril, informed the archaeologists about weird embankments they had found in the steppe. The same evening Zdanovich announced the discovery. The latter would have proven a turning point in the debates about the [[Proto-Indo-European homeland|original homeland of the Indo-Europeans]] and their migrations, which [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] specialists had been bitterly disputing about since the 1970s.{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=33}} The near [[Sintashta culture]], excavated in that decade, yielded the remains of an early [[chariot]] with horses, making apparent that the southern Urals had been a key location in the development of technology and complex civilisation. The discovery of Arkaim confirmed that assumption.{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=34}}
The struggle to rescue the site, was, however, tough, since the reservoir project was carried on by the then all-powerful Ministry of Water Resources of the Soviet Union. The project was scheduled for completion in 1989, but the builders intended to hasten the construction to have it built within the spring of 1988. The archaeologists did their best to mobilise public opinion for the rescue of Arkaim, initially requesting a halt of the project until 1990; academicians and public figures spoke out in their defense. In March 1989 the Praesidium of the Urals Branch of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union formally established a scientific laboratory for the study of the ancient civilisation of Chelyabinsk Oblast, and requested to the Council of Ministers of the Russian Federation to declare the site as a protected area of historical value.{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=35}}
In the following months the Ministry of Water Resources rapidly lost power as the Soviet Union moved towards collapse. In April 1991 the Council of Ministers officially cancelled the construction of the reservoir and declared Arkaim a "historical and geographical museum".{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=35}}
==Structure of Arkaim== [[File:Arkaim Infographic.jpg|thumb|Reconstruction of the Arkaim settlement.]] Arkaim was a circular stronghold, umbegone by two concentric bastions made of adobe with timber frames, and covered with unburnt clay bricks. Within the circles, close to the bastions, were around sixty dwellings with hearth, cellars, wells and metallurgical furnaces. They opened towards an inner circular street paved with wood. The street was lined by a covered drainage gutter with pits for water collection. At the centre of the complex there was a rectangular open space. The complex had four ingangs, consisting of intricately constructed passages and oriented towards the cardinal points. Evidence suggests that the complex was built according to a plan, which indicates that the society had a developed structure of roles and had leaders with great authority.{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=34}}
===Measures=== The settlement covered about {{convert|20000|m2|abbr=off}}. The diameter of the enclosing wall was about {{convert|160|m|abbr=off}}, and its thickness was of {{convert|4|to|5|m|abbr=off}}. The height was of {{convert|5.5|m|ft|2|abbr=off}}. The settlement was surrounded with a {{convert|2|m|abbr=off|adj=on}}-deep moat.
Among the four gates, the main was the western one. The dwellings were between {{convert|110|to|180|m2|sqft|abbr=off}} in area. The dwellings of the outer ring were thirty-nine or forty, with doors opening towards the circular street. The dwellings of the inner ring numbered twenty-seven, arranged along the inner wall, with doors opening towards the central square, which was about {{convert|25|by|27|m|abbr=off}} in area.
Zdanovich estimates that approximately 1,500 to 2,500 people could have lived in Arkaim. Surrounding Arkaim's walls, were arable fields, 130–140 metres by 45 metres (430–460 feet by 150 feet), irrigated by a system of canals and ditches.
==Social impact== ===Religious movements and mysticism=== [[File:Аркаим Гора Шаманка - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Ritual spirals of stones made by Rodnovers in the areas around Arkaim.]] {{Further|Slavic Native Faith in Russia}} The discovery of Arkaim reinvigorated the debate about the [[Proto-Indo-European homeland|original homeland]] of the [[Proto-Indo-Europeans|Indo-Europeans]], seemingly confirming its location in central [[Eurasia]].{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|pp=33–34}} After their discovery, Arkaim and the Land of Towns have been presented as the "land of the [[Aryan]]s", the centre of a statehood of a [[monarchy|monarchical]] type, and ultimately the model for a new spiritual civilisation harmonised with the universe.{{sfnm|1a1=Shnirelman|1y=1998|1p=36|2a1=Shnirelman|2y=2012|2p=27}} Agencies related to the [[Russian Orthodox Church]] have been critical of such activities of Arkaim's archaeology.<ref>{{cite article |last=Petrov |first=Fedor |date=29 June 2010 |title=Наука и неоязычество на Аркаиме (Science and Neopaganism at Arkaim) |website=Proza.ru |url=http://www.proza.ru/2010/05/09/1034 |access-date=3 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707174320/http://www.proza.ru/2010/05/09/1034 |archive-date=7 July 2017}}</ref>
The discovery of Arkaim and the Land of Towns has fueled the growth of schools of thought among [[Rodnovers]], [[Rerikhians]], [[Zoroastrians]] and other movements which regard the archaeological site as the second homeland of the Aryans, who originally dwelt in [[Arctic]] regions and migrated southwards when the weather there became glacial, then spreading from central Eurasia to the east, south and west, founding other civilisations. According to them, all [[Vedas|Vedic]] knowledge originated in the southern Urals.{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=37}} Some of them identify Arkaim as the [[Asgard]] of [[Odin]] spoken of in Germanic literature. The Russian Zoroastrian movement started by the Globa family identifies Arkaim as the place where [[Zoroaster]] was born.{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=38}} Around the year 2005, a great white ''[[swastika]]'' was carved on the nearest hill, and visitors to the site may buy ''swastika''-shaped medallions.{{sfn|Shnirelman|2012|p=28}}
===Vladimir Putin's visit and the "Russian idea"=== Russia's president [[Vladimir Putin]] visited the site in 2005, meeting in person with the chief archaeologist [[Gennady Zdanovich]]. The visit received much attention from Russian media. They presented Arkaim as the "homeland of the majority of contemporary people in Asia, and, partly, Europe". Nationalists called Arkaim the "city of Russian glory" and the "most ancient Slavic-Aryan town". Zdanovich reportedly presented Arkaim to the president as a possible "national idea of Russia",{{sfn|Shnirelman|2012|p=28}} a new idea of civilisation which Shnirelman calls the "Russian idea".{{sfn|Shnirelman|1998|p=36}} According to several analysts, Putin's visit was undoubtedly a message, and it gave credit to the interpretation of Arkaim as an Aryan cult centre.{{sfn|Shnirelman|2012|p=28}}
